# Installation

### Prerequisites

First, you must download KoikatsuModdingTools and the proper Unity version. Follow the steps on their page in the [***How to use it***](https://github.com/IllusionMods/KoikatsuModdingTools?tab=readme-ov-file#how-to-use-it) section, but don’t open Unity yet.

### Adding my tools

Download the latest release on GitHub, then extract it from the .zip, then drag and drop the content into your KoikatsuModdingTools folder. This operation should not ask you to overwrite files, and once done you should have a `/3DSE` folder in `<tools folder>/Assets/Editor`.

Now you can open your KoikatsuModdingTools folder in Unity.

![][image1]  
![][image2]

# New Mod

![][image3]

I recommend using a `Custom` Tab, but if it’s a small mod and you do not plan on expanding it you could use Koikatsu’s default 3D SFX Tab.

### 3DSE Tab		vs		Custom Tab

![][image4]![][image5]

### Mod Fields

![][image6]

#### Mod Name

This name will be used for the `.zipmod` file name and to create a unique identifier. The Search function![][image7] will also consider it.

#### Tab Name

The name that will appear in `Add->Items`. A name longer than 13 characters will scroll horizontally in Studio.

#### First Category \#

If you make multiple mods for the same Tab, make sure your `Categories` are not stepping on each other's foot. This field will tell my tool the starting point of your new mod’s category numbers. You can check `ItemCategory_*.csv` of your previous mod(s) to check where it stopped at or pick a different number.

#### Mod UID

This number will be attributed to your Custom Tab or 3D SFX category and must be unique from other people's mods. If you want to put multiple mods into the same Custom Tab, use the same Tab Name and Mod UID for all of them. Note: The display order in your custom Tab is based on `Mod Name` first, then category numbers.

#### Version

After you release your mod on the internet, make sure you keep the version updated on every new release so CharaStudio can load the proper one if old versions are still installed. For reference, I use this convention:  
1.0.0 \-\> 2.0.0 (Major changes or rework, should alter Mod Name or GUID if it’s not compatible with old version)   
1.0.0 \-\> 1.1.0 (Normal release)  
1.0.0 \-\> 1.0.1 (Quick fix if I messed something up after a release)

### Result

![][image8]

You should now have a new mod in `Assets/Mods`, you can always edit the details using `Edit 3DSE Mod`.

# Generator Pipeline

### Define Categories

![][image9]Audio files go in `<mod>/Sources`, you define categories by creating folders. `Giggle` and `Laugh` will be the 2 categories of my demonstration mod.

### Import Audio

Just drag and drop your files in a category. 

My tools support `.wav` files and can work with `.mp3` if you have the [`ffmpeg library`](https://www.ffmpeg.org/download.html#build-windows) installed and set in your PATH environment variable (If you don’t know what I mean you can just use a program or website to convert mp3 \-\> wav.)  
![][image10]

### Generate 3DSE Items

![][image11]![][image12]

The `ItemXXX*.csv` files in `<mod>/List/Studio/Datafiles` are now populated with 3DSE item and category information for Koikatsu and `<mod>/Prefab` is filled with the items that will be used for the mod.

### Generate mod

Here we KoikatsuModdingTools’ `AssetBundles` tool to convert our items into assets for Koikatsu.  
![][image13]

1) Browse to the location of your Koikatsu folder, where `Koikatu.exe` is located (no it’s not a typo).  
2) Turn off Compression  
3) Click `Build Asset Bundles` and wait for a bit until you see this bottom left (1, 2, doesn’t matter)  
   ![][image14]  
4) Click `Build Zipmod (current)` with your mod selected, or `Build All Zipmods`.   
   ![][image15]

Once done it should appear in your `<Koikatsu install>/mods` folder.  
![][image16]

### Result

By default, my tool will name the items based on the folder structure of a category and assume they are single/non-loop sounds `(S)`. You can customize this behaviour or turn off functions with `Generator Tags`.

# Generator Customization

### 3DSE Tags

You can define tags in `<mod>/Sources` folders and sub-folders to give instructions to the generator on how to handle the names and properties of items created from the sound files in that folder or sub-folder. 

If you define a tag(s) in `<mod>/Sources` then all your items will be affected, if you define it only in `<mod>/Sources/Giggle` then only `Giggle` items will be affected. If you define tags in both, the generator will combine the tags by prioritizing the deepest / latest tags first. 

(will maybe describe each tags later, the examples in the next section are enough to get started)

### 

### Typical Examples

You only need to know these 3 examples: How to disable auto-naming, how to loop, and how to mix tags

#### Disable Auto-Naming

`format-keep-name` will keep the name of your sound file but will format it like so:  
`example-file_A -> ExampleFileA`  
`keep-name will keep the name as is with no modifications.`  
![][image21]

Comparison without VS with `format-keep-name`:

![][image22]

#### Mark As Loop Sound

This will tell the generator that all the items in the folder should play in a loop in Koikatsu, instead of only once.

Here I placed the sound file that should be played as a loop in its own folder, then combined `loop` with `format-keep-name` so that only this item will keep its name and be looped.  
![][image23]

Comparison without VS with `loop` \+ `format-keep-name`:  
![][image24]

#### Combination

Here I set my `Giggle` category to be `format-keep-name` \+ `loop`, but I also created the folder structure `Giggle/High/Slow` and set its tags to `indexed` (for auto-naming) and `no-loop`.

# Fine Tuning

### Audio Properties

I’ll define what they are, then explain how to change them in the next sections.

#### Audio Delay

I add a \~60-70ms delay to the audio of my mods because I found items with a low delay like (S)Pistons from BN2’s mod have a random chance of playing at full volume or making a \**pop*\* when you place the sound item away from X:0 Y:0 Z:0, especially in more computing heavy scenes. My guess is Studio has to move the item every time it plays the sound, and will sometimes play the sound before the move is complete. This is important because the only way to reduce the volume of an item inside Studio is to distance it away.

#### Audio Volume

I set my volume slightly lower than BN2’s `normalmoan1` sound item.

#### Audio Rolloff Distance

At what distance should the item start getting quieter (min) and at what distance should it completely mute (max). I set min to 0.1 and max to 7\. I wouldn’t go lower than 5 for the max.

### Adjust Audio Tool

If you make your own sounds probably don’t need this, but if not it’s a useful tool to normalize your sounds. Select one or more files or folders to adjust them.

Adjusts the delay at the start of the sound. Silence Threshold defines what is considered “silent”, increase it if there is noise at the start.

Adjusts the volume. There is also a (%) adjustement option.

Disable `Overwrite Files` if you wan’t the tool to write the modified sound to a copy.  
This tool is preset with the Delay and Volume described in Audio properties. 

If the silence at the start of your file has noise in it, you might need to increase the Silence Threshold if you want it to properly adjust the delay.

Stereo files ![][image28] will end up louder then Mono files ![][image29]

High pitched sound, like running water, will also probably be too loud at these settings. Same with typically quiet sounds like low breathing.

If you don’t have too many files then I recommend adjusting them individually or in small groups, but if you work with a library with thousands of entries like I did with the OpenNSFW Sound Pack mod then you can do a generic adjustment that works for most and is is too loud for some, then adjust the outliers in Prefab Tuning.

The workflow I use is:

1) Set my categories and item names.  
2) Use `Adjust Audio` with default values on `<mod>/Sources`.  
3) In Prefab Tuning, lower the volume of stereo tracks by 40-50%.  
4) In Prefab Tuning, lower the volume of high pitched or typically quiet sounds by 40-50%.

       (that means lower by 70-75% if it’s both stereo AND high pitched)

5) `Build Asset Bundles` and `Build Zipmod`.  
6) Test inside Studio then go back to Unity and adjust the volumes if necessary.

### Prefab Tuning

Pre-generation, you can modify `<mod>/base_3dse.prefab` to change the base item properties for all items.  
Post-generation, you can modify individual items in `<mod>/Prefab`. These changes will be lost on the next `Create From Source` (use `Update From Source` instead) or if the name of the source is changed.

# Bonus: Item Thumbnails

### In Image Editor

1) [Download paint.net](https://www.dotpdn.com/downloads/pdn.html) or use the editing software of your choice.  
2) Import your reference image, preferably not low quality.  
3) In top left select `Image -> Resize`, enable `By absolute size` and set pixel size to 64 and 64\.  
4) Put this [round square border](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1CJ63HGz3pwyH7T6AaJGJ_SgoETBLL5xi/view?usp=drive_link) on top of it (if you want). The edge color is F5F5F5 so it blends with Studio’s search function without needing transparency which allows a smaller file size.  
5) In top left select `File -> Save As`, set `Save as type` to `.png`, name it `base.png` and click save.  
6) It will then present you with a menu to adjust quality, set `Bit Depth` to 4-bit for minimal file size and play with the `Dithering level`. If your mod does not have many entries you can set a higher quality, just know you need a thumbnail image for every single items.

### In Unity

1) Place your `base.png` (name is important) in `<your mod>/Studio_Thumbs`.  
2) Right click on `Studio_Thumbs` and run `3DSE->Tools->MakeThumbnails.`  
3) `When it’s done, AssetBundle->Build Zipmod (you don’t need to Build Asset Bundles if you did it previously).`
